    <h1>Lumen One Introduction to <em>Psychology</em></h1>
    <p class="subtitle">My longest-running and most successful course, used by more than 200,000 students across the United States. It started as a simple content reformatting project and grew into something I&rsquo;m genuinely proud of: a full courseware system that faculty love teaching and students actually engage with.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="content">

    <!-- OVERVIEW -->
    <div class="case-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Overview</div>
      <h2>Where it started and <em>where it went</em></h2>
      <p>The students who take Introductory Psychology are often navigating real challenges. They might be adjusting to college as first-generation students, working full-time jobs, or be adult learners launching a new career. Psychology is a prerequisite for lots of majors and an important stepping stone for thousands of students.</p>
      <p>The faculty teaching it are frequently adjuncts managing multiple sections with very little time to build materials from scratch. I kept both of those realities in mind throughout every stage of this project.</p>
      <p>Back in its early stages, the course started as an adaptation of OpenStax Psychology content on Lumen&rsquo;s original Candela platform. That first version was largely a reformatting effort with some added assessment items. Over time, through multiple platform generations (Waymaker and then Lumen One), it evolved into something much richer: a full courseware system with original content, thousands of assessment items, instructor-ready classroom activities, and regular updates tied to current research.</p>
      <p>Introductory Psychology is now Lumen Learning&rsquo;s highest-enrolled non-math course, and I continue to develop and refine it.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- ANALYZE + DESIGN -->
    <div class="case-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Analyze &amp; Design</div>
      <h2>Designing around <em>the learner experience</em></h2>
      <p>From the beginning, I wanted this course to feel intentional at every touchpoint. I grounded the design in the APA&rsquo;s Guidelines for the Undergraduate Psychology Major (Version 3.0), with particular attention to the seven APA Integrative Themes, and drew from Gurung and Neufeld&rsquo;s <em>Transforming Introductory Psychology</em> as a framework for making the course genuinely reflect current best practices in the field.</p>
      <p>I collaborated closely with subject matter experts throughout the process, including Patrick Carroll from the University of Texas at Austin and Jessica Traylor from Gordon State College. Working with SMEs is one of my favorite parts of this job. I spend a lot of time getting to know their strengths, drawing out their content expertise, and translating it into materials that work pedagogically. Part of my role is coaching them through that process, and I take that responsibility seriously. I meet my deliverables, I keep projects on timeline, and I try to make the collaboration feel genuinely good for everyone involved.</p>
      <p>One of the most important design decisions was structuring the course around a clear student journey: what happens before class, during class, and after class. This gave faculty a real framework for a flipped or hybrid course, and it gave students a predictable rhythm that reduces cognitive overload and helps them know what to expect.</p>

