    <!-- DEVELOP -->
    <div class="case-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Develop</div>
      <h2>A course that treats students <em>like whole people</em></h2>
      <p>I put a lot of thought into what actually makes content work for students, especially the students who take this course. Psychology is a subject that can feel abstract and distant if it&rsquo;s not connected to real life, so I focused heavily on making the content readable, relatable, and culturally grounded. Long, dense paragraphs got broken up. I added headers to make pages scannable. And I pushed hard to make sure the content didn&rsquo;t just reflect a Western, WEIRD (Western, Educated, Industrialized, Rich, Democratic) view of psychology.</p>
      <p>One of my favorite things about this course is the Psych in Real Life feature. I developed these original narrative examples in collaboration with my SMEs, and they&rsquo;re designed to take abstract psychological concepts and put them in scenarios that actually feel familiar. Students aren&rsquo;t just reading about behavior therapy &mdash; they&rsquo;re reading about Miriam, a business student who&rsquo;s afraid of public speaking, and following along as she works through treatment. That kind of storytelling makes the content stick in a way that a definition never could.</p>

      <div class="slide-showcase">
        <img src="{{ '/images/projects/psych/slide-10.png' | url }}" alt="Culturally Relevant Content — Finding a Therapist, WEIRD populations, Francis Cecil Sumner" />
        <div class="slide-caption">Culturally relevant content is woven throughout rather than siloed. The course addresses WEIRD bias in research, representation in the history of psychology, and culturally competent practice.</div>
      </div>

      <h2>Multiple ways to engage <em>with every topic</em></h2>
      <p>Every section of the course gives students more than one way in. The Learn It pages introduce the core content with embedded practice questions that offer hints and feedback in the moment. Apply It activities push students to actually use what they&rsquo;re learning, not just recall it. Fresh Take pages offer a second angle on the same content through different examples and video. And the Get Stronger review activities and Cheat Sheets give students something to return to when they&rsquo;re studying for exams. I&rsquo;m especially proud of the Apply It activities: we added 77 new ones for Lumen One, covering every major topic across all 16 modules.</p>

      <div class="slide-showcase">
        <img src="{{ '/images/projects/psych/slide-12.png' | url }}" alt="Content in Text slide — Learn It, Apply It, Fresh Take with Miriam example" />
        <div class="slide-caption">Every topic has multiple entry points: Learn It for core content, Apply It for application, and Fresh Take for students who want a different perspective. Psych in Real Life examples like Miriam&rsquo;s story make abstract concepts tangible.</div>
      </div>

      <h2>Leading development <em>from start to finish</em></h2>
      <p>As course product manager, I oversee the entire development process, not just my own contributions. That means recruiting, interviewing, hiring, and training the subject matter experts who bring each piece of the course to life. I work to identify the right people for each project, set them up for success, and give them the coaching and structure they need to produce work that actually meets our instructional and quality standards.</p>
      <p>Development on a course like this is never a solo effort. I collaborate closely with my immediate course development team throughout the process, and then coordinate with a wider group of Lumen Learning colleagues, including people from engineering, sales, and product, to make sure the course works well across the full system and serves the people who need it most. Getting something like this right requires a lot of voices, and part of my job is making sure those conversations happen at the right time and lead somewhere useful.</p>

