    <!-- EVALUATE -->
    <div class="case-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Evaluate</div>
      <h2>A course that <em>keeps getting better</em></h2>
      <p>One of the things I love most about this project is that it never really ends. In 2025 and 2026, all 16 modules were refreshed with more recent research. That meant new content on topics like the gut-brain connection, psychedelic-assisted therapy, AI in hiring, updated sleep research, personality changes across the lifespan, and a significantly expanded treatment of the replication crisis with recent meta-studies. The happiness module got a new optional extension activity on the epidemic of loneliness, grounded in current social connection research.</p>
      <p>This cycle also added a whole set of new classroom activities, developed in response to feedback from faculty who wanted more options for engaging students during class time. Several of these have quickly become favorites.</p>

      <div class="insight-row">
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Sensation &amp; Perception Lab</h3><p>Distortion goggles, blind spot tests, depth perception activities, taste experiments with Skittles. Faculty tell me students still talk about this one at the end of the semester.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Memory Championships</h3><p>An in-class competition that puts memory techniques to the test, including one round where students try to memorize each other&rsquo;s names. It builds both content knowledge and community.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>AI Study Partner</h3><p>Students learn to use AI as a personalized study tool. Faculty reported that students found this genuinely eye-opening; they had never thought of AI as a learning partner before.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Happiness Lab</h3><p>Based on science from Berkeley&rsquo;s Greater Good Science Center, students learn about well-being practices and then actually try them. One of the most-loved activities in the whole course.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Fast Friends</h3><p>Using Aron et al.&rsquo;s 36 Questions for Increasing Closeness, students apply social psychology research while genuinely getting to know each other.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-card"><h3>Psychology Podcast Assignment</h3><p>Students find a psychology podcast they enjoy, then track down the peer-reviewed research behind it. It builds research skills in a format that doesn&rsquo;t feel like homework.</p></div>
      </div>

    </div>

